<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><FONT style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" size=2><B>Fellow
Shareholders:</B></FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We begin our
130<SUP>th</SUP> anniversary year with confidence.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The ways we listen to Customers and respond to their ever-changing needs
have evolved through our history, and yet several clear principles have remained
constant for The Kroger Co. family of stores.</FONT></P>
<UL style="text-align: justify; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our success comes from our people and their
  dedication to making a difference in the lives of our</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Customers;<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We continually seek to strengthen our connection
  with our Customers, which results in<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Consistent returns for
shareholders.</FONT></LI></UL>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Our confidence is firmly rooted in Kroger&#146;s strong foundation for growth.
About 10 years ago we announced our </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Customer
1</FONT></B><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><SUP>st</SUP></FONT></B><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> business strategy</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>, which
truly puts the Customer at the center of how we manage our business. Through our
focus on the Four Keys of our strategy &#150; our people, products, price and the
shopping experience &#150; </FONT><B><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>we are connecting
with Customers in more powerful ways than ever before.</FONT></I></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> Kroger&#146;s identical store sales trend is the clearest measure
of that growing connection. In 2012, Kroger achieved a retail industry-leading
37 consecutive quarters &#150; more than nine years &#150; of positive identical sales
growth.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Late in 2012 we announced </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>aggressive
new growth plans</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> to expand Customer
1<SUP>st</SUP> into the next decade. The Company is investing in a targeted
expansion strategy to increase square footage and store penetration in existing
markets and enter new markets. Through additional capital investments in new and
existing stores, new store formats, and new ways to connect with our Customers
and Associates, including our digital connection, we expect to achieve a higher
long-term financial target and increase Shareholder return.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>A Year of Record Earnings and Focus
on Shareholder Value</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Kroger&#146;s </FONT><B><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>unique
offering</FONT></I></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> of better service, great
products, an enjoyable shopping experience </FONT><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>and</FONT></I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> low prices and weekly specials
continues to resonate with a full range of Customers. As a result, fiscal 2012
sales grew $6.4 billion for total revenue of $96.8 billion, making Kroger
</FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>one of the largest retailers in the
world</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>. Net earnings were $1.5 billion or
$2.77 per diluted share; this includes an $0.11 per diluted share benefit of the
extra week. We achieved record earnings per share for the year, and grew
adjusted net earnings per share by more than 16 percent.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Our outstanding business results allowed Kroger to continue using free
cash flow to reward shareholders. </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We increased
our quarterly dividend by 30 percent</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> and
returned more than $1.5 billion to shareholders through dividends and stock
buybacks in 2012. Since 2006, Kroger has paid nearly $1.6 billion in dividends
to Shareholders. We have been able to accomplish this while maintaining our
investment-grade credit rating and improving our debt leverage ratio and annual
interest expense. </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Since January 2000, Kroger
has returned $9.0 billion to Shareholders through share
repurchases</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Now, what makes this best-in-class performance possible? A large part of
the answer is simple: Our Great People. Associates in the Kroger family of
stores are uniquely and authentically passionate for people and for delivering
superior results. This is brought to life through their dedication to
</FONT><B><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>making the day better</FONT></I></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> for every one of the more than seven million Customers who
shop our stores daily &#150; whether through a simple smile, solving a problem or
helping Customers on a budget feed their family.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>* * *</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Celebration of Our Shared
Heritage</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Barney Kroger opened his first store in Cincinnati, Ohio on July 1, 1883.
That his Company not only survived but is thriving 130 years later is an amazing
accomplishment. And yet two of our banners have been in business even longer. In
1873, George Ralphs &#150; founder of our Ralphs division &#150; opened his first store in
Los Angeles. Ten years earlier, in 1863, John C. Groub &#150; founder of our Jay C
division &#150; opened his first store in Rockford, Indiana.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>We are celebrating the shared heritage of our entire family of stores &#150; a
heritage of transformative growth and innovation that continues to inspire us
today.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">1</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=justify><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Transformative Growth</FONT></I></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Kroger&#146;s
heritage is one of impressive growth &#150; from being the first grocer in the nation
to operate its own bakery in 1901, to operating 37 manufacturing facilities
today; from small grocery stores averaging 3,000 square feet in 1930, to
supermarkets averaging 12,000 square feet in 1960, to today&#146;s Marketplace stores
averaging 125,000 square feet; and from sales topping $1 billion for the first
time in 1952 to sales well over $96 billion in 2012.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Our family of stores has grown by powerful combinations of strong
regional banners, giving the Company the benefits of size without losing the
local touch.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Innovation</FONT></I></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Strengthening our connection with Customers begins with listening to
them, and for 130 years Kroger has developed innovative ways to listen and
respond. In 1959, Kroger executives began conducting &#147;Kroger Calls,&#148;
door-to-door interviews with homemakers, to better understand the needs of our
Customers. In the 1970s we became the first grocer to formalize Customer
research, and last year we listened to nearly 2,000,000 individual Customers and
learned important insights that we use to make merchandising
decisions.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>A more than decade-long partnership with dunnhumbyUSA, the leader in
personalizing Customers&#146; experience of retailers and brands, helps us say that
we know our Customers better than anyone. A great example of how we put this
into practice is through our </FONT><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Loyal Customer
Mailing</FONT></I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>, or LCM, which we send to millions of
households regularly throughout the year. The most recent LCM reached more than
11 million households, and 97 percent of recipients received an individualized
set of coupons for the products they like and buy regularly &#150; </FONT><B><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>almost no two were alike</FONT></I></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>. At redemption rates regularly topping 60 percent, our LCM continues to
lead the industry.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Innovation at Kroger also means utilizing new technologies to meet
Customer needs. In the early 1970s Kroger was the first retailer in the country
to test now-ubiquitous electronic scanners at checkout. In just the last few
years, we have pioneered Que Vision, our innovative faster checkout program that
has reduced the time a Customer waits in line to check out, on average, from
four minutes a few years ago to less than 30 seconds in our stores
today.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Innovation is also at the heart of our sustainability efforts, aimed at
improving today to protect tomorrow. Kroger created an innovative process to
rescue safe, edible fresh products and donate them quickly to local food banks.
This innovation has been replicated by other retailers and today fresh products
make up more than half of the food distributed nationwide by Feeding
America.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>We remain committed to delivering always fresh, high quality and
</FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>sustainably-sourced seafood</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>. We do this in a variety of ways, including support for both
wild-caught and farm-raised fishery improvement projects around the world,
through our partnership with the </FONT><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>World
Wildlife Fund</FONT></I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT><STRONG>We continue to reduce energy use</STRONG></FONT><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>, which lowers our carbon footprint and helps our bottom line. We have
reduced total energy consumption by 32.7 percent since 2000, and are on track to
meet our goal of a 35 percent reduction by 2015. We achieve these efficiencies
in large ways and small, from designing every new store to earn the U.S. EPA
Energy Star rating, to every Associate taking responsibility to turn off lights
and check cooler temperatures throughout the day.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>You can learn more about our sustainability initiatives by reading our
annual sustainability report, available on our website
<U>sustainability.kroger.com</U>.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT><STRONG>Kroger is one of the safest companies in our
industry.</STRONG></FONT><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> Associate engagement in
innovative safety programs has </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>reduced
accident rates</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> in our stores and
manufacturing plants </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>by 76 percent since
1995</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>* * *</FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">2</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=justify><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Celebration of Our
People</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our shared
heritage is the sum total of countless decisions made by Associates through more
than a century in business. We invest in our Associates and their families in a
variety of ways, including:</FONT></P>
<UL style="text-align: justify; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>In 2012, Kroger spent more than $1.7 billion to
  </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>provide health care benefits</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Through the </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Kroger Scholars fund</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>, we provide
  scholarships to children of Associates so they</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>can further their dreams. In the last five years, Kroger has provided
  scholarships to 1,500 children</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>of
  Associates.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We take care of each other through the most
  challenging circumstances &#150; such as the loss of a home due</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>to a natural disaster &#150; through our </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Helping Hands </FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>program.</FONT></LI></UL>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>A distinct point of pride and celebration for us is the longevity of so
many of our Associates. Currently, more than 13,000 of our more than 343,000
Associates have served our Customers for more than 30 years. Nearly 2,000
Associates have served for more than 40 years.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>* * *</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Enduring Value of Supporting
Communities</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Over the years, Kroger has undergone several reinventions to meet the
changing needs of American families. One thing that has not changed is our
ability to make a difference in the lives of our Customers and communities. We
partner with local communities through our commitment to feeding the hungry and
supporting women&#146;s health, the military and their families, and local
organizations and schools.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>In 2012, Kroger:</FONT></P>
<UL style="text-align: justify; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Delivered the </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>largest contribution of food and funds </FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>in Kroger&#146;s history, the equivalent of nearly 200</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>million meals, to </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Feeding
  America </FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>and its local food
  banks.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Engaged vendors and Customers to contribute
  </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>more than nearly $5.9 million in support of
  women&#146;s</FONT></B> <B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>health and breast cancer
  awareness programs</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Delivered </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>$3.3
  million to the USO </FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>to help them in their
  work supporting the military and their families.</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>This is the largest one-time gift to the USO in that organization&#146;s
  history.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Supported more than </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>30,000 schools </FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>and local
  organizations through our Community Rewards Program</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>that delivers personalized, Customer-driven donations based on total
  purchases.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Contributed an additional $8.2 million to local
  organizations supporting our communities through The</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Kroger Co. Foundation. In the past five years, our foundation has
  donated $37.4 million.</FONT></LI></UL>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>We do these things because our Customers tell us it is important to them
and because it strengthens the communities we call home. When you combine the
cash, food and product we donate to a variety of causes and programs,
</FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Kroger contributed more than $250
million</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> in 2012 to support the communities we
serve.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Kroger is a leader in supplier diversity, spending more than
</FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>$1 billion annually with women- and
minority-owned businesses</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>. We proudly remain
a member of the </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Billion Dollar
Roundtable</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> and the </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>United States Hispanic Chamber of Commerce </FONT></B><B><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Million Dollar Club</FONT></I></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>* * *</FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">3</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=justify><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The Year Ahead</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Kroger is on
pace to deliver another record year. Revenues will approach $100 billion for the
first time.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>We will continue to </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>execute our
Customer 1</FONT></B><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><SUP>st</SUP></FONT></B><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> Strategy</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>, coupled with our
</FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>renewed commitment to growth</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>, to make a difference for Customers and create value for
Shareholders in 2013. By targeting capital investments to grow our business in
new and existing markets and leveraging dunnhumby insights to solve varied
Customer needs, we expect to achieve fully diluted earnings per share growth of
8% to 11% plus the dividend over time.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>As you can see, the future is bright for Kroger. We are bullish about our
ability to sustain the strong momentum that we generated in 2012. In many ways,
our fiscal 2012 results served as a great example of our ability to continually
grow. We are enthusiastic about all that is to come in the year ahead, which
will surely be an exciting and significant one for Kroger.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>On behalf of the entire Kroger family, thank you for your continued trust
and support.</FONT></P><IMG src="kroger_def14a1x6x1.jpg" border=0> <BR>
<DIV align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>David B. Dillon<BR></FONT><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Chairman of the Board and<BR>Chief Executive
Officer</FONT></DIV>

BALLROOM, MUSIC HALL, 1241 Elm Street, Cincinnati, Ohio 45202, on June 27, 2013,
at 11 a.m., eastern time, for the following purposes:</FONT></P>

<P align=left><FONT style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" size=2><B>Attendance</B></FONT></P>

</FONT>Only shareholders and persons holding proxies from shareholders may
attend the meeting. </FONT><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>If you are attending the
meeting, please bring the notice of the meeting that was separately mailed to
you or the top portion of your proxy card, either of which will serve as your
admission ticket</FONT></B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

REPRESENTED AT THE MEETING, IN PERSON OR BY PROXY. PLEASE VOTE YOUR PROXY
ELECTRONICALLY VIA THE INTERNET OR BY TELEPHONE. IF YOU HAVE ELECTED TO RECEIVE
PRINTED MATERIALS, YOU MAY SIGN AND DATE THE PROXY AND MAIL IT IN THE
SELF-ADDRESSED ENVELOPE PROVIDED. NO POSTAGE IS REQUIRED IF MAILED WITHIN THE
UNITED STATES.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>If you are unable to attend the annual meeting, you may listen to a live
webcast of the meeting, which will be accessible through our website,
ir.kroger.com, at 11 a.m., eastern time.</FONT></P>

<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">6</FONT></B></P>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><FONT style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" size=2><B>Proxy
Statement</B></FONT></P>
<P align=right><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Cincinnati, Ohio, May 14, 2013</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Your proxy is
solicited by the Board of Directors of The Kroger Co., and the cost of
solicitation will be borne by Kroger. We will reimburse banks, brokers,
nominees, and other fiduciaries for postage and reasonable expenses incurred by
them in forwarding the proxy material to their principals. Kroger has retained
D.F. King &amp; Co., Inc., 48 Wall Street, New York, New York, to assist in the
solicitation of proxies and will pay that firm a fee estimated at present not to
exceed $15,000. Proxies may be solicited personally, by telephone,
electronically via the Internet, or by mail.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>David B. Dillon, John T. LaMacchia, and Bobby S. Shackouls, all of whom
are Kroger directors, have been named members of the Proxy Committee.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The principal executive offices of The Kroger Co. are located at 1014
Vine Street, Cincinnati, Ohio 45202-1100. Our telephone number is 513-762-4000.
This Proxy Statement and Annual Report, and the accompanying proxy, were first
furnished to shareholders on May 14, 2013.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>As of the close of business on April 30, 2013, our outstanding voting
securities consisted of 520,063,320 common shares, the holders of which will be
entitled to one vote per share at the annual meeting. The shares represented by
each proxy will be voted unless the proxy is revoked before it is exercised.
Revocation may be in writing to Kroger&#146;s Secretary, or in person at the meeting,
or by appointment of a subsequent proxy. Shareholders may not cumulate votes in
the election of directors.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The effect of broker non-votes and abstentions on matters presented for
shareholder vote is as follows:</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT><STRONG>Item No. 1, Election of Directors</STRONG></FONT><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> &#150; An affirmative majority of the total number of votes cast &#147;for&#148; or
&#147;against&#148; a director nominee is required for election. Accordingly, broker
non-votes and abstentions will have no effect on this proposal.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT><STRONG>Item No. 2, Advisory Vote to Approve Executive
Compensation</STRONG></FONT><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> &#150; Approval by shareholders
of executive compensation requires the affirmative vote of the majority of
shares participating in the voting. Accordingly, broker non-votes and
abstentions will have no effect on this proposal.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT><STRONG>Item No. 3, Selection of Auditors</STRONG></FONT><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> &#150; Ratification by shareholders of the selection of independent public
accountants requires the affirmative vote of the majority of shares
participating in the voting. Accordingly, abstentions will have no effect on
this proposal.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT><STRONG>Item Nos. 4, 5, 6 and 7, Shareholder
Proposals</STRONG></FONT><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> &#150; The affirmative vote of a
majority of shares participating in the voting on a shareholder proposal is
required for its adoption. Proxies will be voted AGAINST these proposals unless
the Proxy Committee is otherwise instructed on a proxy properly executed and
returned. Broker non-votes and abstentions will have no effect on these
proposals.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">7</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><FONT style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" size=2><B>Proposals to Shareholders</B></FONT></P>
<P align=center><FONT style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" size=2><B>Election of Directors<BR>(Item No. 1) </B></FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The Board of
Directors, as now authorized, consists of fourteen members. All members are to
be elected at the annual meeting to serve until the annual meeting in 2014, or
until their successors have been elected by the shareholders or by the Board of
Directors pursuant to Kroger&#146;s Regulations, and qualified. Kroger&#146;s Articles of
Incorporation provide that the vote required for election of a director by the
shareholders, except in a contested election or when cumulative voting is in
effect, will be the affirmative vote of a majority of the votes cast for or
against the election of a nominee.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The experience, qualifications, attributes, and skills that led the
Corporate Governance Committee and the Board to conclude that the following
individuals should serve as directors are set forth opposite each individual&#146;s
name. The committee memberships stated below are those in effect as of the date
of this proxy statement. It is intended that, except to the extent that
authority is withheld, proxies will be voted for the election of the following
persons:</FONT></P>

    <TD vAlign=top noWrap  align=left width="1%" bgColor=#c0c0c0></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top  align=center width="81%" bgColor=#c0c0c0>
      <P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Ms. Kropf was President and Chief
      Operating Officer of Avon Products Inc., a manufacturer and marketer of
      beauty care products, from 2001 until her retirement in January 2007. She
      joined Avon in 1970. Prior to her most recent assignment, Ms. Kropf had
      been Executive Vice President and Chief Operating Officer, Avon North
      America and Global Business Operations from 1998 to 2000. From 1997 to
      1998 she was President, Avon U.S. Ms. Kropf was a member of Avon&#146;s Board
      of Directors from 1998 to 2006. She currently is a member of the Board of
      Directors of Coach, Inc., MeadWestvaco Corporation, and Sherwin Williams
      Company. She is a member of the Audit and Financial Policy
      Committees.</FONT></P>
      <P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Ms. Kropf has gained a unique
      consumer insight, having led a major beauty care company. She has
      extensive experience in manufacturing, marketing, supply chain operations,
      customer service, and product development, all of which assist her in her
      role as a member of Kroger&#146;s Board. Ms. Kropf has
      a strong financial background, and has served on compensation, audit, and
      corporate governance committees of other boards. She was inducted into the
      YWCA Academy of Women Achievers.</FONT></P></TD>

    <TD vAlign=top noWrap align=left width="1%" bgColor=#c0c0c0></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top align=center width="81%" bgColor=#c0c0c0>
      <P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Dr. Phillips is Professor
      Emeritus of Finance at The George Washington University School of
      Business. She joined that university as a Professor and Dean in 1998. She
      retired as Dean of the School of Business as of June 30, 2010, and as
      Professor the following year. She was a member of the Board of Governors
      of the Federal Reserve System from December 1991 through June 1998. Before
      her Federal Reserve appointment, Dr. Phillips served as Vice President for
      Finance and University Services and Professor of Finance in The College of
      Business Administration at the University of Iowa from 1987 through 1991.
      She is a director of CBOE Holdings, Inc., State Farm Mutual Automobile
      Insurance Company, State Farm Life Insurance Company, State Farm Companies
      Foundation, National Futures Association, the Chicago Board Options
      Exchange, and Agnes Scott College. Dr. Phillips also was a trustee of the
      Financial Accounting Foundation until the end of 2010. She is a member of
      the Audit and Compensation Committees.</FONT></P>
      <P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Dr. Phillips brings to the Board
      strong financial acumen, along with a deep understanding of, and
      involvement with, the relationship between corporations and the
      government. Her experience in academia brings a unique and diverse
      viewpoint to the deliberations of the Board. Dr. Phillips has been
      designated an Audit Committee financial expert.</FONT></P></TD>

    <TD vAlign=top noWrap align=center width="3%"></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD vAlign=top noWrap align=center width="10%" bgColor=#c0c0c0>
      <P align=justify><B><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Ronald L.
      Sargent</FONT></B></P></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top noWrap align=left width="1%" bgColor=#c0c0c0></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top align=center width="81%" bgColor=#c0c0c0>
      <P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Mr. Sargent is Chairman and Chief
      Executive Officer of Staples, Inc., a consumer products retailer, where he
      has been employed since 1989. Prior to joining Staples, Mr. Sargent spent
      10 years with Kroger in various positions. In addition to serving as a
      director of Staples, Mr. Sargent is a director of Five Below, Inc. During
      the past five years, he was a director of Mattel, Inc. and The Home Depot,
      Inc. Mr. Sargent is chair of the Audit Committee and a member of the
      Public Responsibilities Committee.</FONT></P>
      <P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Mr. Sargent has over 30 years of
      retail experience, first with Kroger and then with increasing levels of
      responsibility and leadership at Staples, Inc. His efforts helped carve
      out a new market niche for the international retailer that he leads. His
      understanding of retail operations and consumer insights are of particular
      value to the Board. Mr. Sargent has been designated an Audit Committee
      financial expert.</FONT></P></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top noWrap align=left width="1%" bgColor=#c0c0c0></TD>

      <P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Until the merger of Burlington
      Resources Inc. and ConocoPhillips, which became effective in 2006, Mr.
      Shackouls was Chairman of the Board of Burlington Resources Inc., a
      natural resources business, since July 1997 and its President and Chief
      Executive Officer since December 1995. He had been a director of that
      company since 1995 and President and Chief Executive Officer of Burlington
      Resources Oil and Gas Company (formerly known as Meridian Oil Inc.), a
      wholly-owned subsidiary of Burlington Resources, since 1994. Mr. Shackouls
      is a director of PNGS GP LLC, the general partner of PAA Natural Gas
      Storage, L.P., and Oasis Petroleum Inc. During the past five years, Mr.
      Shackouls was a director of ConocoPhillips. He has been appointed by
      Kroger&#146;s Board to serve as Lead Director. Mr. Shackouls is chair of the
      Corporate Governance Committee and a member of the Audit
      Committee.</FONT></P>
      <P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Mr. Shackouls brings to the Board
      the critical thinking that comes with a chemical engineering background.
      His guidance of a major natural resources company, coupled with his
      corporate governance expertise, forms the foundation of his leadership
      role on Kroger&#146;s Board.</FONT></P></TD>
