  <TR>
    <TD vAlign=top noWrap><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>(4)</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="100%"><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Amounts include
      contractual interest payments using the interest rate as of February 2,
      2013, and stated fixed and swapped interest rates, if applicable, for all
      other debt instruments.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD vAlign=top colSpan=2>&nbsp;</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD vAlign=top noWrap><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>(5)</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="100%"><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The amounts included
      in the contractual obligations table for self-insurance liability related
      to workers&#146; compensation claims have been stated on a present value
      basis.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our
construction commitments include funds owed to third parties for projects
currently under construction. These amounts are reflected in other current
liabilities in our Consolidated Balance Sheets.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Our purchase obligations include commitments to be utilized in the normal
course of business, such as several contracts to purchase raw materials utilized
in our manufacturing plants and several contracts to purchase energy to be used
in our stores and manufacturing facilities. Our obligations also include
management fees for facilities operated by third parties. Any upfront vendor
allowances or incentives associated with outstanding purchase commitments are
recorded as either current or long-term liabilities in our Consolidated Balance
Sheets.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>As of February 2, 2013, we maintained a $2 billion (with the ability to
increase by $500 million), unsecured revolving credit facility that, unless
extended, terminates on January 25, 2017. Outstanding borrowings under the
credit agreement and commercial paper borrowings, and some outstanding letters
of credit, reduce funds available under the credit agreement. In addition to the
credit agreement, we maintained two uncommitted money market lines totaling $75
million in the aggregate. The money market lines allow us to borrow from banks
at mutually agreed upon rates, usually at rates below the rates offered under
the credit agreement. As of </FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-25</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>February 2, 2013, we had $1.6 billion
of borrowings of commercial paper and no borrowings under our credit agreement
and money market lines. The outstanding letters of credit that reduce funds
available under our credit agreement totaled $13 million as of February 2,
2013.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>In addition to
the available credit mentioned above, as of February 2, 2013, we had authorized
for issuance $700 million of securities under a shelf registration statement
filed with the SEC and effective on December 15, 2010. On January 18, 2013, the
Board of Directors authorized for issuance additional securities in the amount
of $1.8 billion over and above the $700 million of securities available for
issuance as of February 2, 2013. Subsequent to year-end, we filed a Current
Report on Form 8-K, on February 11, 2013, incorporating by reference additional
exhibits to the shelf registration statement including the Board of Directors&#146;
resolution.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>We also maintain surety bonds related primarily to our self-insured
workers&#146; compensation claims. These bonds are required by most states in which
we are self-insured for workers&#146; compensation and are placed with predominately
third-party insurance providers to insure payment of our obligations in the
event we are unable to meet our claim payment obligations up to our self-insured
retention levels. These bonds do not represent liabilities of Kroger, as we
already have reserves on our books for the claims costs. Market changes may make
the surety bonds more costly and, in some instances, availability of these bonds
may become more limited, which could affect our costs of, or access to, such
bonds. Although we do not believe increased costs or decreased availability
would significantly affect our ability to access these surety bonds, if this
does become an issue, we would issue letters of credit, in states where allowed,
against our credit facility to meet the state bonding requirements. This could
increase our cost and decrease the funds available under our credit
facility.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>We have guaranteed half of the indebtedness of two real estate entities
in which we have a 50% ownership interest. Our share of the responsibility for
this indebtedness, should the entities be unable to meet their obligations,
totals approximately $6 million. Based on the covenants underlying this
indebtedness as of February 2, 2013, we believe that it is unlikely that we will
be responsible for repayment of these obligations.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>We also are contingently liable for leases that have been assigned to
various third parties in connection with facility closings and dispositions. We
could be required to satisfy obligations under the leases if any of the
assignees are unable to fulfill their lease obligations. Due to the wide
distribution of our assignments among third parties, and various other remedies
available to us, we believe the likelihood that we will be required to assume a
material amount of these obligations is remote. We have agreed to indemnify
certain third-party logistics operators for certain expenses, including pension
trust fund contribution obligations and withdrawal liabilities.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>In addition to the above, we enter into various indemnification
agreements and take on indemnification obligations in the ordinary course of
business. Such arrangements include indemnities against third party claims
arising out of agreements to provide services to Kroger; indemnities related to
the sale of our securities; indemnities of directors, officers and employees in
connection with the performance of their work; and indemnities of individuals
serving as fiduciaries on benefit plans. While Kroger&#146;s aggregate
indemnification obligation could result in a material liability, we are not
aware of any current matter that could result in a material
liability.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" size=2><STRONG>Outlook </STRONG></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>This discussion and analysis contains certain forward-looking statements
about Kroger&#146;s future performance. These statements are based on management&#146;s
assumptions and beliefs in light of the information currently available. Such
statements relate to, among other things: projected changes in net earnings
attributable to The Kroger Co.; identical supermarket sales growth; expected
product cost; expected pension plan contributions; our ability to generate
operating cash flows; projected capital expenditures; square footage growth;
opportunities to reduce costs; cash flow requirements; and our operating plan
for the future; and are indicated by words such as &#147;comfortable,&#148; &#147;committed,&#148;
&#147;will,&#148; &#147;expect,&#148; &#147;goal,&#148; &#147;should,&#148; &#147;intend,&#148; &#147;target,&#148; &#147;believe,&#148; &#147;anticipate,&#148;
&#147;plan,&#148; and similar words or phrases. These forward-looking statements are
subject to uncertainties and other factors that could cause actual results to
differ materially.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-26</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Statements
elsewhere in this report and below regarding our expectations, projections,
beliefs, intentions or strategies are forward-looking statements within the
meaning of Section 21E of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934. While we believe
that the statements are accurate, uncertainties about the general economy, our
labor relations, our ability to execute our plans on a timely basis and other
uncertainties described below could cause actual results to differ
materially.</FONT></P>
<UL style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; text-align: justify"><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We expect net earnings per diluted share in the
  range of $2.71-$2.79 for 2013. This equates to our long-term growth rate of 8% to 11% from our adjusted fiscal 2012
  net earnings per diluted share of $2.52,</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>which
  excludes the UFCW consolidated pension accrual and credit card settlement
  adjustments in the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>third quarter of 2012 and
  the extra week in the fourth quarter of 2012. We expect the first
  quarter</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>net earnings per diluted share growth
  rate for 2013 to be on the low end of the range primarily due to</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>expected inflation being lower in the first quarter of 2013,
  compared to 2012, and the growth of our</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>pharmacy business not being as substantial as in the first quarter of
  2012. We expect the second and</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>third quarters
  net earnings per diluted share growth rate for 2013 to be at the high end to
  above the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>range primarily due to expected
  inflation being more comparable in the second and third quarters of</FONT>
  <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>2013, compared to the second and third quarters of
  2012, and expecting our identical supermarket sales</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>to be trending upwards. We also expect the fourth quarter net earnings
  per diluted share growth rate</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>for 2013 to be
  lower than the prior year on a 12-week to 12-week basis primarily due to a
  budgeted LIFO</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>charge of $13 million compared to
  a LIFO credit of $41 million in the fourth quarter of 2012.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We expect identical supermarket sales growth,
  excluding fuel sales, of 2.5%-3.5% in 2013. We expect</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>identical supermarket sales growth to increase over time during 2013
  relative to 2012. In 2012, we</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>experienced
  higher levels of inflation early in the year. In the second half of the year,
  several branded</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>prescription drugs came off
  patent, and when branded prescription drugs come off patent and are
  sold</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>as generics, sales are reduced because
  generic equivalents have lower retail prices than branded drugs. </FONT><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We do not expect these conditions to continue to have the
  same impact for 2013.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our long-term business model seeks to produce
  annual earnings per diluted share growth averaging</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>8.0%-11.0%, plus a dividend of 2.0% to 2.5%, for a total shareholder
  return of approximately 10.0%-13.5%.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>For 2013, we intend to continue to focus on
  improving sales growth, in accordance with our Customer</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>1<SUP>st </SUP>strategy, by making investments in gross
  margin and customer shopping experiences. We expect to</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>finance these investments primarily with operating cost reductions. We
  expect FIFO non-fuel operating</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>margins for 2013
  to expand slightly compared to 2012, excluding the UFCW consolidated pension
  plan</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>accrual and the credit card settlement
  adjustments in 2012.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>For 2013, we expect our annualized LIFO charge to
  be approximately $55 million. This forecast is based</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>on estimated cost changes for products in our inventory.</FONT>
<BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>For 2013, we expect interest expense to be
  approximately $440 million.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We plan to use cash flow primarily for capital
  investments, to maintain our current debt coverage ratios,</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>to pay cash dividends, and to repurchase stock. As market
  conditions change, we may re-evaluate these</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>uses of cash flow.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We expect to obtain sales growth from new square
  footage, as well as from increased productivity from</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>existing locations.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Capital investments reflect our strategy of growth
  through expansion, filling in targeted existing markets,</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>entering a new market and focusing on productivity increases
  from our existing store base through</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>remodels.
  In addition, we intend to continue our emphasis on self-development and
  ownership of real</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>estate, and logistics and
  technology improvements. Our continued capital spending on technology
  is</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>focused on improving store operations,
  logistics, manufacturing procurement, category management,</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>merchandising and buying practices, and is expected to
  reduce merchandising costs. We intend to</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>continue using cash flow from operations to finance capital expenditure
  requirements. We expect capital</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>investments for
  2013 to increase to the range of $2.1-$2.4 billion, excluding acquisitions and
  purchases</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>of leased facilities. We also expect
  capital investments to increase incrementally $200 million over the</FONT>
  </LI></UL>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-27</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P style="PADDING-LEFT: 30pt" align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>next few
years, excluding acquisitions and purchases of leased facilities, to accomplish
our strategy. We expect total food store square footage for 2013 to grow
approximately 1.5% before acquisitions and operational closings. </FONT></P>
<UL style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Based on current operating trends, we believe that
  cash flow from operations and other sources of</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>liquidity, including borrowings under our commercial paper program and
  bank credit facility, will be</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>adequate to meet
  anticipated requirements for working capital, capital expenditures, interest
  payments</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>and scheduled principal payments for
  the foreseeable future. We also believe we have adequate coverage</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>under our debt covenants to continue to respond effectively
  to competitive conditions.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We believe we have adequate sources of cash, if
  needed, under our credit facility and other borrowing</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>sources for the next twelve months and for the foreseeable future
  beyond the next twelve months.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We expect that our OG&amp;A results will be
  affected by increased costs, such as higher employee benefit</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>costs and credit card fees, offset by improved productivity
  from process changes and leverage gained</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>through sales increases.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We expect that our effective tax rate for 2013
  will be approximately 35.5%, excluding the effect of the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>resolution of any tax issues.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We expect rent expense, as a percentage of total
  sales and excluding closed-store activity, will decrease</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>due to the emphasis our current strategy places on ownership
  of real estate.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We believe that in 2013 there will be
  opportunities to reduce our operating costs in such areas as</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>administration, productivity improvements, shrink,
  warehousing and transportation. We intend to invest</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>most of these savings in our core business to drive profitable sales
  growth and offer improved value and</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>shopping
  experiences for our customers.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>In February 2013, we contributed $100 million to
  the Company-sponsored defined benefit pension</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>plans and do not expect to make any additional contributions in 2013.
  We expect contributions made</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>during 2013 will
  decrease our required contributions in future years. Among other things,
  investment</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>performance of plan assets, the
  interest rates required to be used to calculate the pension
  obligations,</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>and future changes in legislation,
  will determine the amounts of additional contributions. We expect</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>2013 expense for Company-sponsored defined benefit pension
  plans to be approximately $80 million. </FONT><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>In
  addition, we expect 401(k) Retirement Savings Account Plan cash contributions
  and expense from</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>automatic and matching
  contributions to participants to increase slightly in 2013, compared to
  2012.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We expect to contribute approximately $225 million
  to multi-employer pension plans in 2013, subject to</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>collective bargaining. In addition, excluding all payments to the UFCW
  consolidated pension plan and</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>the pension plans
  that were consolidated into the UFCW consolidated pension plan, we expect
  increases</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>in expense as a result of increases
  in multi-employer pension plan contributions over the next few years.</FONT>
  <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We do not anticipate additional goodwill
  impairments in 2013.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>In 2013, we expect to refinance $1.5 billion of
  debt. We plan on refinancing our debt maturities in 2013</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>along with an additional issuance of approximately $500
  million to replace the senior notes bearing an</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>interest rate of 5.5% that matured in the fourth quarter of 2012. The
  debt that matured in the fourth</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>quarter of 2012
  was previously refinanced with commercial paper.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We have various labor agreements that will be
  renegotiated in 2013, covering store employees in</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Indianapolis, Dallas, Houston, Seattle and Cincinnati, among others.
  Upon the expiration of our</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>collective
  bargaining agreements, work stoppages by the affected workers could occur if
  we are unable</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>to negotiate new contracts with
  labor unions. A prolonged work stoppage affecting a substantial number</FONT>
  <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>of locations could have a material adverse effect on
  our results. In all of these contracts, rising health care</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>and pension costs will continue to be an important issue in
  negotiations.</FONT> </LI></UL>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-28</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P style="PADDING-LEFT: 30pt" align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Various
uncertainties and other factors could cause us to fail to achieve our goals.
These include:</FONT></P>
<UL style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The extent to which our sources of liquidity are
  sufficient to meet our requirements may be affected by</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>the state of the financial markets and the effect that such condition
  has on our ability to issue commercial</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>paper at
  acceptable rates. Our ability to borrow under our committed lines of credit,
  including our</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>bank credit facilities, could be
  impaired if one or more of our lenders under those lines is unwilling
  or</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>unable to honor its contractual obligation
  to lend to us, or in the event that natural disasters or weather</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>conditions interfere with the ability of our lenders to lend
  to us. Our ability to refinance maturing debt</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>may be affected by the state of the financial markets.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Changes in market conditions could affect our cash
  flow.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our ability to achieve sales and earnings goals
  may be affected by: labor negotiations or disputes; changes in</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>the types and numbers of businesses that compete with us;
  pricing and promotional activities of existing</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>and new competitors, including non-traditional competitors, and the
  aggressiveness of that competition;</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>our
  response to these actions; the state of the economy, including interest rates,
  the inflationary and</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>deflationary trends in
  certain commodities, and the unemployment rate; the effect that fuel costs
  have</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>on consumer spending; changes in
  government-funded benefit programs; manufacturing commodity</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>costs; diesel fuel costs related to our logistics
  operations; trends in consumer spending; the extent to</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>which our customers exercise caution in their purchasing in response to
  economic conditions; the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>inconsistent pace of
  the economic recovery; changes in inflation or deflation in product and
  operating</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>costs; stock repurchases; the effect
  of brand prescription drugs going off patent; our ability to retain</FONT>
  <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>additional pharmacy sales from third party payors; and
  the success of our future growth plans. The</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>extent to which the adjustments we are making to our strategy create
  value for our shareholders will</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>depend
  primarily on the reaction of our customers and our competitors to these
  adjustments, as well</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>as operating conditions,
  including inflation or deflation, increased competitive activity, and
  cautious</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>spending behavior of our customers.
  Our ability to achieve sales and earnings goals may also be affected</FONT>
  <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>by our ability to manage the factors identified
  above.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our product cost inflation could vary from our
  estimate due to general economic conditions, weather,</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>availability of raw materials and ingredients in the products that we
  sell and their packaging, and other</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>factors
  beyond our control.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our ability to pass on product cost increases will
  depend on the reactions of our customers and</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>competitors to those increases.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our ability to use free cash flow to continue to
  maintain our debt coverage and to reward our shareholders</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>could be affected by unanticipated increases in net total
  debt, our inability to generate free cash flow at</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>the levels anticipated, and our failure to generate expected
  earnings.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>During the first three quarters of the year, our
  LIFO charge and the recognition of LIFO expense will be</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>affected primarily by estimated year-end changes in product
  costs. Our LIFO charge for the year will be</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>affected primarily by changes in product costs at year-end.</FONT>
<BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>If actual results differ significantly from
  anticipated future results for certain reporting units including</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>variable interest entities, an impairment loss for any
  excess of the carrying value of the reporting units&#146;</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>goodwill over the implied fair value would have to be
  recognized.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>In addition to the factors identified above, our
  identical store sales growth could be affected by increases</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>in Kroger private label sales, the effect of our &#147;sister
  stores&#148; (new stores opened in close proximity to an</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>existing store) and reductions in retail pricing.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our operating margins, without fuel, could decline
  or fail to meet expectations if we are unable to pass</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>on any cost increases, if we fail to deliver the cost savings
  contemplated or if changes in the cost of our</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>inventory and the timing of those changes differ from our
  expectations.</FONT> </LI></UL>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-29</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<UL style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We have estimated our exposure to the claims and
  litigation arising in the normal course of business,</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>as well as to the material litigation facing Kroger, and believe we
  have made provisions where it is</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>reasonably
  possible to estimate and where an adverse outcome is probable. Unexpected
  outcomes in</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>these matters, however, could
  result in an adverse effect on our earnings.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Changes in the types and numbers of businesses
  that compete with us are likely to continue and the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>effects on our business, either favorable or unfavorable, cannot be
  foreseen.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Rent expense, which includes subtenant rental
  income, could be adversely affected by the state of the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>economy, increased store closure activity and future
  consolidation.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Depreciation expense, which includes the
  amortization of assets recorded under capital leases, is</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>computed principally using the straight-line method over the
  estimated useful lives of individual assets,</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>or
  the remaining terms of leases. Use of the straight-line method of depreciation
  creates a risk that future</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>asset write-offs or
  potential impairment charges related to store closings would be larger than if
  an</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>accelerated method of depreciation were
  followed.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our effective tax rate may differ from the
  expected rate due to changes in laws, the status of pending</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>items with various taxing authorities, and the deductibility
  of certain expenses.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The actual amount of automatic and matching cash
  contributions to our 401(k) Retirement Savings</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Account Plan will depend on the number of participants, savings rate,
  compensation as defined by the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>plan, and length
  of service of participants.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The amounts of our contributions and recorded
  expense related to multi-employer pension funds could</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>vary from the amounts that we expect, and could increase more than
  anticipated. Should asset values in</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>these funds
  deteriorate, if employers withdraw from these funds without providing for
  their share of the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>liability, or should our
  estimates prove to be understated, our contributions could increase more
  rapidly</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>than we have anticipated.</FONT>
  <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>If the investment performance of our pension plan
  assets does not meet expectations due to poor</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>performance of the financial markets or for other reasons, our
  contributions to Company-sponsored</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>defined
  benefit pension plans could increase more than anticipated in future
  periods.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Changes in laws or regulations, including changes
  in accounting standards, taxation requirements and</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>environmental laws may have a material effect on our financial
  statements.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Changes in the general business and economic
  conditions in our operating regions may affect the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>shopping habits of our customers, which could affect sales and
  earnings.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Changes in our product mix may negatively affect
  certain financial indicators. For example, we continue</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>to add supermarket fuel centers to our store base. Since gasoline
  generates low profit margins, we</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>expect to see
  our FIFO gross profit margins decline as gasoline sales increase. Although
  this negatively</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>affects our FIFO gross margin,
  gasoline sales provide a positive effect on OG&amp;A expense as a
  percentage</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>of sales.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our capital expenditures, expected square footage
  growth, and number of store projects completed</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>over the next fiscal year could differ from our estimate if we are
  unsuccessful in acquiring suitable sites</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>for
  new stores, if development costs vary from those budgeted, if our logistics
  and technology or store</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>projects are not
  completed on budget or within the time frame projected, or if economic
  conditions fail</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>to improve, or worsen.</FONT>
  <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Interest expense could be adversely affected by
  the interest rate environment, changes in our credit</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>ratings, fluctuations in the amount of outstanding debt, decisions to
  incur prepayment penalties on the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>early
  redemption of debt and any factor that adversely affects our operations and
  results in an increase</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>in debt.</FONT>
  <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Impairment losses, including goodwill, could be
  affected by changes in our assumptions of future cash</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>flows, market values or business valuations in the market. Our cash
  flow projections include several</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>years of
  projected cash flows which would be affected by changes in the economic
  environment, real</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>estate market values,
  competitive activity, inflation and customer behavior.</FONT> </LI></UL>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-30</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<UL style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Our estimated expense and obligation for
  Kroger-sponsored pension plans and other post-retirement</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>benefits could be affected by changes in the assumptions
  used in calculating those amounts. These</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>assumptions include, among others, the discount rate, the expected
  long-term rate of return on plan</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>assets,
  average life expectancy and the rate of increases in compensation and health
  care costs.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Adverse weather conditions could increase the cost
  our suppliers charge for their products, or may</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>decrease customer demand for certain products. Increases in demand for
  certain commodities could</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>also increase the
  cost our suppliers charge for their products. Additionally, increases in the
  cost of</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>inputs, such as utility costs or raw
  material costs, could negatively affect financial ratios and earnings.</FONT>
  <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Although we presently operate only in the United
  States, civil unrest in foreign countries in which our</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>suppliers do business may affect the prices we are charged for imported
  goods. If we are unable to pass</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>on these
  increases to our customers, our FIFO gross margin and net earnings would
  suffer.</FONT> <BR>&nbsp;
  </LI><LI><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Earnings and sales also may be affected by natural
  disasters or adverse weather conditions, particularly to</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>the extent that they disrupt our operations or those of our
  suppliers; create shortages in the availability</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>or increases in the cost of products that we sell in our stores or
  materials and ingredients we use in our</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>manufacturing facilities; or raise the cost of supplying energy to our
  various operations, including the</FONT> <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>cost of
  transportation.</FONT> </LI></UL>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>We cannot
fully foresee the effects of changes in economic conditions on Kroger&#146;s
business. We have assumed economic and competitive situations will not change
significantly in 2013.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Other factors and assumptions not identified above could also cause
actual results to differ materially from those set forth in the forward-looking
information. Accordingly, actual events and results may vary significantly from
those included in, contemplated or implied by forward-looking statements made by
us or our representatives.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-31</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>
<!-- PART i -->
<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><FONT style="FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" face="Times New Roman" size=2><STRONG>Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting
Firm</STRONG></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT size=2 face="Times New Roman">To the Shareowners and Board of Directors
of<BR>The Kroger Co.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>In our
opinion, the accompanying consolidated balance sheets and the related
consolidated statements of operations, comprehensive income, cash flows and
changes in shareowners&#146; equity present fairly, in all material respects, the
financial position of The Kroger Co. and its subsidiaries at February 2, 2013
and January 28, 2012, and the results of their operations and their cash flows
for each of the three years in the period ended February 2, 2013 in conformity
with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.
Also in our opinion, the Company maintained, in all material respects, effective
internal control over financial reporting as of February 2, 2013, based on
criteria established in </FONT><I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Internal Control -
Integrated Framework</FONT></I><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2> issued by the Committee
of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO). The Company&#146;s
management is responsible for these financial statements, for maintaining
effective internal control over financial reporting and for its assessment of
the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting, included in
Management&#146;s Report on Internal Control over Financial Reporting appearing on
page A-1. Our responsibility is to express opinions on these financial
statements and on the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting based
on our integrated audits. We conducted our audits in accordance with the
standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States).
Those standards require that we plan and perform the audits to obtain reasonable
assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material
misstatement and whether effective internal control over financial reporting was
maintained in all material respects. Our audits of the financial statements
included examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and
disclosures in the financial statements, assessing the accounting principles
used and significant estimates made by management, and evaluating the overall
financial statement presentation. Our audit of internal control over financial
reporting included obtaining an understanding of internal control over financial
reporting, assessing the risk that a material weakness exists, and testing and
evaluating the design and operating effectiveness of internal control based on
the assessed risk. Our audits also included performing such other procedures as
we considered necessary in the circumstances. We believe that our audits provide
a reasonable basis for our opinions.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>A company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting is a process
designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial
reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in
accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. A company&#146;s internal
control over financial reporting includes those policies and procedures that (i)
pertain to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable detail, accurately and
fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of the assets of the company;
(ii) provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as necessary to
permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted
accounting principles, and that receipts and expenditures of the company are
being made only in accordance with authorizations of management and directors of
the company; and (iii) provide reasonable assurance regarding prevention or
timely detection of unauthorized acquisition, use, or disposition of the
company&#146;s assets that could have a material effect on the financial
statements.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Because of its inherent limitations, internal control over financial
reporting may not prevent or detect misstatements. Also, projections of any
evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that
controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the
degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may
deteriorate.</FONT></P><IMG src="kroger_def14a9x1x1.jpg" border=0> <BR>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Cincinnati, Ohio<BR>April 2,
2013</FONT></P>

<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-37</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><B><FONT style="FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" face="Times New Roman" size=2>Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>All dollar amounts are in millions
except share and per share amounts.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Certain prior-year amounts have been
reclassified to conform to current year presentation.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><B><FONT style="FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" face="Times New Roman" size=2>1.
Accounting Policies&nbsp;</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The following
is a summary of the significant accounting policies followed in preparing these
financial statements.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><I>Description of
Business, Basis of Presentation and Principles of Consolidation</I></font></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Kroger Co. (the &#147;Company&#148;) was founded in 1883 and incorporated in
1902. As of February 2, 2013, the Company was one of the largest retailers in
the United States based on annual sales. The Company also manufactures and
processes food for sale by its supermarkets. The accompanying financial
statements include the consolidated accounts of the Company, its wholly-owned
subsidiaries and the Variable Interest Entities (&#147;VIEs&#148;) in which the Company is
the primary beneficiary. Significant intercompany transactions and balances have
been eliminated.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><I>Fiscal
Year</I></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company&#146;s fiscal year ends on the Saturday nearest January 31. The
last three fiscal years consist of the 53-week period ended February 2, 2013 and
the 52-week periods ended January 28, 2012 and January 29, 2011.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><I>Pervasiveness of
Estimates</I></FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The
preparation of financial statements in conformity with generally accepted
accounting principles (&#147;GAAP&#148;) requires management to make estimates and
assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities.
Disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities as of the date of the
consolidated financial statements and the reported amounts of consolidated
revenues and expenses during the reporting period also is required. Actual
results could differ from those estimates.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><I>Inventories</I></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Inventories are stated at the lower of cost (principally on a last-in,
first-out &#147;LIFO&#148; basis) or market. In total, approximately 96% and 97% of
inventories for 2012 and 2011, respectively, were valued using the LIFO method.
Cost for the balance of the inventories, including substantially all fuel
inventories, was determined using the first-in, first-out (&#147;FIFO&#148;) method.
Replacement cost was higher than the carrying amount by $1,098 at February 2,
2013 and $1,043 at January 28, 2012. The Company follows the Link-Chain,
Dollar-Value LIFO method for purposes of calculating its LIFO charge or
credit.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The item-cost method of accounting to determine inventory cost before the
LIFO adjustment is followed for substantially all store inventories at the
Company&#146;s supermarket divisions. This method involves counting each item in
inventory, assigning costs to each of these items based on the actual purchase
costs (net of vendor allowances and cash discounts) of each item and recording
the cost of items sold. The item-cost method of accounting allows for more
accurate reporting of periodic inventory balances and enables management to more
precisely manage inventory when compared to the retail method of accounting. In
addition, substantially all of the Company&#146;s inventory consists of finished
goods and is recorded at actual purchase costs (net of vendor allowances and
cash discounts).</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company evaluates inventory shortages throughout the year based on
actual physical counts in its facilities. Allowances for inventory shortages are
recorded based on the results of these counts to provide for estimated shortages
as of the financial statement date.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-38</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><B><FONT style="FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" face="Times New Roman" size=2>Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements, Continued</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><I>Property, Plant and
Equipment</I></FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Property,
plant and equipment are recorded at cost. Depreciation expense, which includes
the amortization of assets recorded under capital leases, is computed
principally using the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of
individual assets. Buildings and land improvements are depreciated based on
lives varying from 10 to 40 years. All new purchases of store equipment are
assigned lives varying from three to nine years. Leasehold improvements are
amortized over the shorter of the lease term to which they relate, which varies
from four to 25 years, or the useful life of the asset. Manufacturing plant and
distribution center equipment is depreciated over lives varying from three to 15
years. Information technology assets are generally depreciated over five years.
Depreciation and amortization expense was $1,652 in 2012, $1,638 in 2011 and
$1,600 in 2010.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Interest costs on significant projects constructed for the Company&#146;s own
use are capitalized as part of the costs of the newly constructed facilities.
Upon retirement or disposal of assets, the cost and related accumulated
depreciation are removed from the balance sheet and any gain or loss is
reflected in net earnings.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><I>Deferred
Rent</I></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company recognizes rent holidays, including the time period during
which the Company has access to the property for construction of buildings or
improvements and escalating rent provisions on a straight-line basis over the
term of the lease. The deferred amount is included in Other Current Liabilities
and Other Long-Term Liabilities on the Company&#146;s Consolidated Balance
Sheets.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT><EM>Goodwill</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company reviews goodwill for impairment during the fourth quarter of
each year, and also upon the occurrence of trigger events. The reviews are
performed at the operating division level. Generally, fair value is determined
using a multiple of earnings, or discounted projected future cash flows, and is
compared to the carrying value of a division for purposes of identifying
potential impairment. Projected future cash flows are based on management&#146;s
knowledge of the current operating environment and expectations for the future.
If potential for impairment is identified, the fair value of a division is
measured against the fair value of its underlying assets and liabilities,
excluding goodwill, to estimate an implied fair value of the division&#146;s
goodwill. Goodwill impairment is recognized for any excess of the carrying value
of the division&#146;s goodwill over the implied fair value. Results of the goodwill
impairment reviews performed during 2012, 2011 and 2010 are summarized in Note 2
to the Consolidated Financial Statements.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><I>Impairment of
Long-Lived Assets</I></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company monitors the carrying value of long-lived assets for
potential impairment each quarter based on whether certain trigger events have
occurred. These events include current period losses combined with a history of
losses or a projection of continuing losses or a significant decrease in the
market value of an asset. When a trigger event occurs, an impairment calculation
is performed, comparing projected undiscounted future cash flows, utilizing
current cash flow information and expected growth rates related to specific
stores, to the carrying value for those stores. If the Company identifies
impairment for long-lived assets to be held and used, the Company compares the
assets&#146; current carrying value to the assets&#146; fair value. Fair value is based on
current market values or discounted future cash flows. The Company records
impairment when the carrying value exceeds fair market value. With respect to
owned property and equipment held for sale, the value of the property and
equipment is adjusted to reflect recoverable values based on previous efforts to
dispose of similar assets and current economic conditions. Impairment is
recognized for the excess of the carrying value over the estimated fair market
value, reduced by estimated direct costs of disposal. The Company recorded asset
impairments in the normal course of business totaling $18, $37 and $25 in 2012,
2011 and 2010, respectively. Costs to reduce the carrying value of long-lived
assets for each of the years presented have been included in the Consolidated
Statements of Operations as &#147;Operating, general and administrative&#148;
expense.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-39</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><B><FONT style="FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" face="Times New Roman" size=2>Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements, Continued</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><I>Store Closing
Costs</I></FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The Company
provides for closed store liabilities relating to the present value of the
estimated remaining non-cancellable lease payments after the closing date, net
of estimated subtenant income. The Company estimates the net lease liabilities
using a discount rate to calculate the present value of the remaining net rent
payments on closed stores. The closed store lease liabilities usually are paid
over the lease terms associated with the closed stores, which generally have
remaining terms ranging from one to 20 years. Adjustments to closed store
liabilities primarily relate to changes in subtenant income and actual exit
costs differing from original estimates. Adjustments are made for changes in
estimates in the period in which the change becomes known. Store closing
liabilities are reviewed quarterly to ensure that any accrued amount that is not
a sufficient estimate of future costs, or that no longer is needed for its
originally intended purpose, is adjusted to income in the proper
period.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Owned stores held for disposal are reduced to their estimated net
realizable value. Costs to reduce the carrying values of property, equipment and
leasehold improvements are accounted for in accordance with the Company&#146;s policy
on impairment of long-lived assets. Inventory write-downs, if any, in connection
with store closings, are classified in &#147;Merchandise costs.&#148; Costs to transfer
inventory and equipment from closed stores are expensed as incurred.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The following table summarizes accrual activity for future lease
obligations of stores that were closed in the normal course of
business:</FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT><EM>Interest Rate Risk Management</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company uses derivative instruments primarily to manage its exposure
to changes in interest rates. The Company&#146;s current program relative to interest
rate protection and the methods by which the Company accounts for its derivative
instruments are described in Note 6.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT><EM>Commodity Price Protection</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company enters into purchase commitments for various resources,
including raw materials utilized in its manufacturing facilities and energy to
be used in its stores, manufacturing facilities and administrative offices. The
Company enters into commitments expecting to take delivery of and to utilize
those resources in the conduct of the normal course of business. The Company&#146;s
current program relative to commodity price protection and the methods by which
the Company accounts for its purchase commitments are described in Note
6.</FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-40</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><B><FONT style="FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" face="Times New Roman" size=2>Notes to Consolidated
Financial Statements, Continued</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><I>Benefit Plans and
Multi-Employer Pension Plans</I></FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The Company
recognizes the funded status of its retirement plans on the Consolidated Balance
Sheet. Actuarial gains or losses, prior service costs or credits and transition
obligations that have not yet been recognized as part of net periodic benefit
cost are required to be recorded as a component of Accumulated Other
Comprehensive Income (&#147;AOCI&#148;). All plans are measured as of the Company&#146;s fiscal
year end.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The determination of the obligation and expense for Company-sponsored
pension plans and other post-retirement benefits is dependent on the selection
of assumptions used by actuaries and the Company in calculating those amounts.
Those assumptions are described in Note 13 and include, among others, the
discount rate, the expected long-term rate of return on plan assets and the
rates of increase in compensation and health care costs. Actual results that
differ from the assumptions are accumulated and amortized over future periods
and, therefore, generally affect the recognized expense and recorded obligation
in future periods. While the Company believes that the assumptions are
appropriate, significant differences in actual experience or significant changes
in assumptions may materially affect the pension and other post-retirement
obligations and future expense.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company also participates in various multi-employer plans for
substantially all union employees. Pension expense for these plans is recognized
as contributions are funded. Refer to Note 14 for additional information
regarding the Company&#146;s participation in these various multi-employer plans and
the United Food and Commercial Workers International Union (&#147;UFCW&#148;) consolidated
fund.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company administers and makes contributions to the employee 401(k)
retirement savings accounts. Contributions to the employee 401(k) retirement
savings accounts are expensed when contributed. Refer to Note 13 for additional
information regarding the Company&#146;s benefit plans.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Stock Based Compensation</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company accounts for stock options under fair value recognition
provisions. Under this method, the Company recognizes compensation expense for
all share-based payments granted. The Company recognizes share-based
compensation expense, net of an estimated forfeiture rate, over the requisite
service period of the award. In addition, the Company records expense for
restricted stock awards in an amount equal to the fair market value of the
underlying stock on the grant date of the award, over the period the awards
lapse.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Deferred Income Taxes</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Deferred income taxes are recorded to reflect the tax consequences of
differences between the tax basis of assets and liabilities and their financial
reporting basis. Refer to Note 4 for the types of differences that give rise to
significant portions of deferred income tax assets and liabilities. Deferred
income taxes are classified as a net current or noncurrent asset or liability
based on the classification of the related asset or liability for financial
reporting purposes. A deferred tax asset or liability that is not related to an
asset or liability for financial reporting is classified according to the
expected reversal date.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Uncertain Tax Positions</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company reviews the tax positions taken or expected to be taken on
tax returns to determine whether and to what extent a benefit can be recognized
in its consolidated financial statements. Refer to Note 4 for the amount of
unrecognized tax benefits and other related disclosures related to uncertain tax
positions.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Various taxing authorities periodically audit the Company&#146;s income tax
returns. These audits include questions regarding the Company&#146;s tax filing
positions, including the timing and amount of deductions and the allocation of
income to various tax jurisdictions. In evaluating the exposures connected with
these various tax filing positions, including state and local taxes, the Company
records allowances for probable exposures. A number of years may elapse before a
particular matter, for which an allowance has been established, is audited and
fully resolved. As of February 2, 2013, the Internal Revenue Service had
concluded its field examination </FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-41</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><B><FONT style="FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" face="Times New Roman" size=2>Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements, Continued</FONT></B></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>of the Company&#146;s 2008 and 2009 federal
tax returns. The Company has filed an administrative appeal within the Internal
Revenue Service protesting certain adjustments proposed by the Internal Revenue
Service as a result of their field work.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The assessment
of the Company&#146;s tax position relies on the judgment of management to estimate
the exposures associated with the Company&#146;s various filing positions.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Self-Insurance Costs</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company is primarily self-insured for costs related to workers&#146;
compensation and general liability claims. Liabilities are actuarially
determined and are recognized based on claims filed and an estimate of claims
incurred but not reported. The liabilities for workers&#146; compensation claims are
accounted for on a present value basis. The Company has purchased stop-loss
coverage to limit its exposure to any significant exposure on a per claim basis.
The Company is insured for covered costs in excess of these per claim
limits.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The following table summarizes the changes in the Company&#146;s
self-insurance liability through February 2, 2013.</FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The current portion of the self-insured liability is included in &#147;Other
current liabilities,&#148; and the long-term portion is included in &#147;Other long-term
liabilities&#148; in the Consolidated Balance Sheets.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The Company is
also similarly self-insured for property-related losses. The Company maintains
stop loss coverage to limit its property loss exposures including coverage for
earthquake, wind, flood and other catastrophic events.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Revenue Recognition</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Revenues from the sale of products are recognized at the point of sale.
Discounts provided to customers by the Company at the time of sale, including
those provided in connection with loyalty cards, are recognized as a reduction
in sales as the products are sold. Discounts provided by vendors, usually in the
form of paper coupons, are not recognized as a reduction in sales provided the
coupons are redeemable at any retailer that accepts coupons. The Company records
a receivable from the vendor for the difference in sales price and cash
received. Pharmacy sales are recorded when provided to the customer. Sales taxes
are recorded as other accrued liabilities and not as a component of sales. The
Company does not recognize a sale when it sells its own gift cards and gift
certificates. Rather, it records a deferred liability equal to the amount
received. A sale is then recognized when the gift card or gift certificate is
redeemed to purchase the Company&#146;s products. Gift card and certificate breakage
is recognized when redemption is deemed remote and there is no legal obligation
to remit the value of the unredeemed gift card. The amount of breakage has not
been material for 2012, 2011 and 2010.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Merchandise Costs</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The &#147;Merchandise costs&#148; line item of the Consolidated Statements of
Operations includes product costs, net of discounts and allowances; advertising
costs (see separate discussion below); inbound freight charges; warehousing
costs, including receiving and inspection costs; transportation costs; and
manufacturing production and operational costs. Warehousing, transportation and
manufacturing management salaries </FONT></P>
<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-42</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>
<!-- PART J -->

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><FONT style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" size=2><B>Notes
to Consolidated Financial Statements, Continued</B></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>are also included in the &#147;Merchandise
costs&#148; line item; however, purchasing management salaries and administration
costs are included in the &#147;Operating, general, and administrative&#148; line item
along with most of the Company&#146;s other managerial and administrative costs. Rent
expense and depreciation expense are shown separately in the Consolidated
Statements of Operations.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>Warehousing
and transportation costs include distribution center direct wages, repairs and
maintenance, utilities, inbound freight and, where applicable, third party
warehouse management fees, as well as transportation direct wages and repairs
and maintenance. These costs are recognized in the periods the related expenses
are incurred.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company believes the classification of costs included in merchandise
costs could vary widely throughout the industry. The Company&#146;s approach is to
include in the &#147;Merchandise costs&#148; line item the direct, net costs of acquiring
products and making them available to customers in its stores. The Company
believes this approach most accurately presents the actual costs of products
sold.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company recognizes all vendor allowances as a reduction in
merchandise costs when the related product is sold. When possible, vendor
allowances are applied to the related product cost by item and, therefore,
reduce the carrying value of inventory by item. When the items are sold, the
vendor allowance is recognized. When it is not possible, due to systems
constraints, to allocate vendor allowances to the product by item, vendor
allowances are recognized as a reduction in merchandise costs based on inventory
turns and, therefore, recognized as the product is sold.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Advertising Costs</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The Company&#146;s advertising costs are recognized in the periods the related
expenses are incurred and are included in the &#147;Merchandise costs&#148; line item of
the Consolidated Statements of Operations. The Company&#146;s pre-tax advertising
costs totaled $553 in 2012, $532 in 2011 and $533 in 2010. The Company does not
record vendor allowances for co-operative advertising as a reduction of
advertising expense.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Deposits In-Transit</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Deposits in-transit generally represent funds deposited to the Company&#146;s
bank accounts at the end of the year related to sales, a majority of which were
paid for with credit cards and checks, to which the Company does not have
immediate access but that settle within a few days of the sales
transaction.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Consolidated Statements of Cash
Flows</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>For purposes of the Consolidated Statements of Cash Flows, the Company
considers all highly liquid debt instruments purchased with an original maturity
of three months or less to be temporary cash investments. Book overdrafts, which
are included in accounts payable, represent disbursements that are funded as the
item is presented for payment. Book overdrafts totaled $839, $718 and $699 as of
February 2, 2013, January 28, 2012 and January 29, 2011, respectively, and are
reflected as a financing activity in the Consolidated Statements of Cash
Flows.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Accumulated Other Comprehensive (Loss)
Income</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Accumulated other comprehensive (loss) income, net of applicable taxes,
consisted of the following at year-end:</FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" size=2><B>Notes
to Consolidated Financial Statements, Continued</B></FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><EM>Segments</EM></FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>The Company
operates retail food and drug stores, multi-department stores, jewelry stores,
and convenience stores throughout the United States. The Company&#146;s retail
operations, which represent over 99% of the Company&#146;s consolidated sales and
EBITDA, are its only reportable segment. The Company&#146;s retail operating
divisions have been aggregated into one reportable segment due to the operating
divisions having similar economic characteristics with similar long-term
financial performance. In addition, the Company&#146;s operating divisions offer to
its customers similar products, have similar distribution methods, operate in
similar regulatory environments, purchase the majority of the Company&#146;s
merchandise for retail sale from similar (and in many cases identical) vendors
on a coordinated basis from a centralized location, serve similar types of
customers, and are allocated capital from a centralized location. The Company&#146;s
operating divisions reflect the manner in which the business is managed and how
the Company&#146;s Chief Executive Officer and Chief Operating Officer, who act as
the Company&#146;s chief operating decision makers, assess performance internally.
All of the Company&#146;s operations are domestic.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The following table presents sales revenue by type of product for 2012,
2011 and 2010.</FONT></P>

<P align=center><B><FONT face="Times New Roman">A-44</FONT></B></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=center><FONT style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-VARIANT: small-caps" size=2><B>Notes
to Consolidated Financial Statements, Continued</B></FONT></P>
<P align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2>In 2012, the
Company acquired an interest in one of its suppliers and all the outstanding
shares of Axium Pharmacy, a leading specialty pharmacy that provides specialized
drug therapies and support services for patients with complex medical
conditions, resulting in combined additional goodwill of $96.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Testing for impairment must be performed annually, or on an interim basis
upon the occurrence of a triggering event or a change in circumstances that
would more likely than not reduce the fair value of a reporting unit below its
carrying amount. The annual evaluation of goodwill performed during the fourth
quarter of 2012 and 2011 did not result in impairment.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The annual evaluation of goodwill performed during the fourth quarter of
2010 resulted in an impairment charge of $18. Based on the results of the
Company&#146;s step one analysis in the fourth quarter of 2010, a supermarket
reporting unit with a small number of stores indicated potential impairment. Due
to estimated future expected cash flows being lower than in the past, the
estimated fair value of the reporting unit decreased. Management concluded that
the carrying value of goodwill for this reporting unit exceeded its implied fair
value, resulting in a pre-tax impairment charge of $18 ($12 after-tax). In 2009,
the Company disclosed that a 10% reduction in fair value of this supermarket
reporting unit would indicate a potential for impairment. Subsequent to the
impairment, no goodwill remains at this reporting unit.</FONT></P>
<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>Based on current and future expected cash flows, the Company believes
goodwill impairments are not reasonably possible. A 10% reduction in fair value
of the Company&#146;s reporting units would not indicate a potential for impairment
of the Company&#146;s remaining goodwill balance.</FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="Times New Roman" size=2><FONT size=3 face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>The 2011 effective tax rate was significantly lower than 2012 and 2010
due to the effect on pre-tax income of the UFCW consolidated pension plan charge
of $953 ($591 after-tax) in 2011. The effect of the UFCW consolidated pension
plan charge reduced pre-tax income thereby increasing the effect of credits and
of the favorable resolution of tax issues on our 2011 effective tax
rate.</FONT></P>
